default&#xa0;
defaultThe system currently being promoted by the Coalition gov
defaulternment is based on competition between areas for both funds and powers at the same time. There are drawbacks to a system based on bidding, which are that the areas which may be most in need of support may also be those which have less capacity to mount go
defaultod bids. In all areas the resources available for 
default any 
default function which is not front line service delivery are intensely squeezed. This may be of particular concern to 
defaultruraldefault areas with dispersed populations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Smith Institute has reported on current arr
defaultangements to East Midlands Councils and concluded that “if funds are awarded to areas that happen to have the most developed capacity to bid successfully, rather than necessarily the strongest case in terms of need and opportunity, then that investment wil
defaultl have a less than optimal impact, as well as reinforcing entrenched 
defaultinequalities
default”
default Yet in the UK as a whole there is already a formula-based system of devolution to Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, so the principle of a non-bidding system has been ac
defaultcepted. 
default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the variable geometry arising from a bidding system,
default 
defaultWhitehall departments and their agencies 
defaultwill
default need to become astute in undertaking negotiations with the devolved areas regarding cross border issues. Probably the most serious of these would be matters of housing, transport and economic growth across the boundary of Greater London.  As things curren
defaulttly stand, the appetite for effective joint working to be rewarded by devolution is weakest in the parts of England adjoining London. Unless this changes, it poses serious challenges to planning the area which produces nearly 40% of UK GDP.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultGoing further with the current bidding system 
default(despite its disadvantages) 
defaultwould have the 
defaultbenefit
default of providing opportunities for increased capacit
defaulty building and also sharing of best practice from areas with more evolved levels of cooperation. However given the time required to instigate more fundamental reform it would be preferable for 
defaultthe two processes to take place in paralle
defaultl
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe continued 
defaultsqueeze on local authority capacity and resources may result in some areas exploring fundamental change (such as Shropshire did recently, choosing voluntary unitary status). Likew
defaulti
defaultse the constraints on resour
defaultc
defaultes and capacity in 
defaultWhitehall 
default 
defaultwill necessitate 
defaultnew approaches, greater departmental alignment and hopefully more devolution and empowerment.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultAs the Local Government Association has indicated
default, t
defaulthe long term 
defaultfinancial 
defaultsustainability of local government in its current fo
defaultrm is 
defaultenormously challenging
default. A recent past in which high levels of centralisation have been combined with (and to an extent justified by) high levels of central government spending looks likely to be gone for some time, if not for good. Alternatives could
default include more ability to raise 
defaultand allocate 
defaultmoney locally, with taxing land in one form or other being a possibility. 
